english:
  title: Three Quatrains in Six-Word Verse on the Road to Yongcheon
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    All night in the traveler's inn I listened to the rain,
    A single point of blue lamplight, and I wrote my poems.
    The road stretches long—the wanderer wakes before dawn,
    The mud runs deep—the relay horse moves slowly on.

    Deep in the forest, I hear the nightingale's song but cannot see it,
    On this long journey, trust your horse and carry only feeling.
    Looking back and forth through the ages of mankind,
    How many times has heaven and earth turned from shadow into light?

    My sleeves are soaked through with the damp of evening tears,
    The cloud-wrapped forest lining the path knows no end.
    On the wild waters, fish leap upon the mirror's face,
    And through the spring mountains, birds pass beyond the folding screen.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem uses the six-word (육언) meter, a classical form favored in Korean poetry that creates a distinctive rhythmic pattern.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'folding screen' (屛心) in the final line suggests both the literal landscape and the romantic conventions of East Asian poetry, where mountains and birds are traditional symbols of spiritual transcendence.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem captures the liminal experience of travel—the speaker suspended between departure and arrival, between observation and introspection.
